cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      1. Opener's Jump Shift      }
^-|cs||fp||va|4|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|It continually amazes me how many "intermediate" players have been improperly taught (or improperly remember) this topic. Read carefully: A Jump-shift by opener is GAME FORCING. It shows a very big hand. It does not show a 16- or 17-count. ^*BGot it?^*N

Let's look at a few examples:|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


NT||
ST||sk|n|MD|1S4HA 2DA Q J 9 2CA K J 3 2,,,|sv|o|rh||AH|Board 1|mb|1dp1hp3c|an|jump-shift|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|Opener should have something like this hand.|SK||
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


at|

However, opener should not have a hand like the next one.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


NT||
%%%
ST||sk|s|MD|1S4H8 2DK Q J 9 2CA K Q 3 2,,,|sv|o|rh||AH|Board 2|mb|1dp1hp?|NT|^B@2
With this hand,|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT| opener has to rebid 2@C (in tempo, please). He is not nearly strong enough to jumpshift. When opener rebids in a new suit without jumping, he can have up to 18 points!|MB|2C|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


NT||

ST||sk|n|MD|1SA 3HA Q J 2D2CA K J 6 5 2,,,|sv|o|rh||AH|Board 3|mb|1cp1dp2h|an|jump-shift|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


NT|^B@2
With this bidding, opener should have something like this hand.|SK||
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


at|

However, opener should not have a hand like the next one.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT||
%%%
ST||sk|s|MD|1S4HK J 9 2DA 2CA Q J 8 3 2,,,|sv|o|rh||AH|Board 4|mb|1cp1dp?|NT|^B@2
With this hand, opener should not bid 2@H.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT|^B@2
With the latter hand, opener has to rebid 1@H (again, in tempo'don't indicate that you have extras by taking a long time). Opener is not nearly strong enough to force to game with a jumpshift.|MB|1h|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT|^B@2
So, opener's jumpshift is a huge bid, showing almost a strong 2-bid. Not only is it forcing (partner cannot pass), but it is forcing all the way until game is reached. |
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


NT|^B@2
The only way to stop short of game is if responder breaks system and just decides to pass, maybe because he has responded with a 2-count or the like.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Note: A 2NT rebid (as a jumpshift) is the obvious exception. That action shows 18-19 balanced, and can be passed. |
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


