qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      2. Opener's Reverse      }
^-|cs||fp||va|4|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N^*N|cp||at|This can be a complex subject. "What is a reverse?" Technically, there are several ways to describe it, all of them confusing. Here is one way to define a reverse:

a nonjump bid by opener at the two-level in a new suit that ranks higher than the suit opener bid first. Also, this applies only if responder's bid was on the 1-level. Ugh! Better to look at a few example auctions of a reverse by opener:|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Before his examples and to expand Cohen's definition of a reverse further, let me define it as follows:

^*B1)^*N Opener makes a bid in a new suit that is higher than bidding his original suit at the 2-level. For example:|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


HT|l|cs|6|at|^B{|ia|,1dp1sp!2h|at|}|HT|l|at|^L@2This auction is a reverse because 2@H is higher than 2@D.|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


HT|p|at|^B{|ia|,1dp1sp!2c|at|}|ht|p|at|^L@2But this auction is not a reverse because 2@C is lower than 2@D.|
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


HT|t|at|^B{|ia|,1dp1sp!2s|at|}|ht|t|at|^L@2Also, the auction on the left is not a reverse. Although 2@S is past 2@D, 2@S is not a new suit. It is simply a raise showing a minimum opener (13-16 Bergen dummy points) and 4 (occasionally 3) spades.|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


HT|x|at|^B@2^*B2)^*N Opener must be able to bid his original suit at the 2-level in order for it to be a reverse. Thus, if it goes 1@C-P-1@S-2@D-2@H, 2H is not a reverse because 2C was not available as a bid. However, if it goes 1@D-P-1@S-2@C-2@H, 2@H is a reverse because 2@D was available as a bid.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||
%%%
ST||MD|1,,,|sv|o|rh||AH|Board 5|mb|1cp1hp2d|an|Reverse - new suit on the 2-level|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|Notice that in this auction, the opener bid a new suit on the two-level in a higher-ranking suit than his first suit. |
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Such a bid shows extras. Why? Because if the responder now were to go back (take a preference) to opener's first suit, he would have to go up one more level (to the three-level). Opener had better have a good hand to survive such a preference. How good?|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT|^B@2 
A reverse shows at least 16-18 playing points. I won't get into how to add for distribution at this point. Suffice to say, that the modern-day treatment is to count extra for long suits. Add for short suits, only after a trump-fit has been established.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


NT|^B@2
So, on this auction, the hand opener might have is as shown above.|md|0S5HJ 4 3DA Q J 9CA K Q 5 4,0,0,0|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


NT|^B@2
On the other hand, opener should ^*Bnot^*N have this hand|md|1S4 HQ J 2 DA Q J 9 CK J 5 3 2|sv|o|rh||AH|Board 5a|mb|1cp1hp2d|an|you cannot bid this|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


NT|^B@2
This hand is not strong enough to reverse.|
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


NT||
