qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      AFTER OPENER REVERSES      }
^-|fp||ht|c|va|6|at|^B@2If the responder rebids his suit, it shows 5 cards and is forcing one round, but not to game. For example in this auction:|
ht|e|at|^b{|ia|,1dp1sp2hp2s|at|}|ht|e|at|^k@22@S = (5+ S, forcing one round).|
pg| ***** 45 ***** |


ht|h|va|5|at|^b{|ia|,1dp1sp2hp2n|at|}|ht|h|va|5|at|^k@2If the responder bids the cheapest new suit (or 2NT if that is cheaper), he is showing a weak hand. He can pass opener's next bid. (2NT bid in this auction shows a weak hand'the responder can pass opener's next bid).|
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


ht|l|VA|4|at|^b{|ia|,1dp1sp2hp3d|at|}|ht|l|VA|4|at|^k@2If the responder does anything else, it is natural and forcing to game. (3@D here is natural, game forcing).|
pg| ***** 47 ***** |


HT|p|at|^B@2Notes: There is confusion (rightly so) over other "reverse" auctions. For example, in this auction,|

ht|q|va|4|at|^b{|ia|,1hp2cp2s|at|}|ht|q|va|4|at|^k@22@S is a "reverse?", but does it show extras if playing that 2@C was already GF? There is no universal answer, but I say that in a 2/1 GF auction, there should be no such thing as "reverses" -- i.e., they don't show extras. |
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


AT|Also, in this auction is| 


ht|u|va|4|at|^b{|ia|,1sp2hp3c|at|}|ht|u|va|4|at|^k@23@C a reverse? |
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


AT|Again, no consensus, but I recommend that it doesn't promise extras. There are other auctions where it is not clear if opener has reversed, nor whether he has promised extras. Also, the explanation given in this article is just a summary'it doesn't cover all the nuances. However, it already says more than I wanted to say'this is supposed to be a KISS (Keep it Simple') summary.|
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


