qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{    AFTER OPENER REVERSES - Comments by Howard Schutzman   }
^-|fp||ht|c|va|6|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Reverse auctions are complicated because the reverse does not establish a game force. Sometimes responder must take charge of the auction and make sure their side gets to game. Sometimes opener must take charge and make sure their side gets to game. And sometimes neither partner has enough to force to game.|
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


AT|

Cohen's system of the cheapest of 2N and the 4th suit as indicating that responder has a weak hand that cannot force to game is played by many. But it is flawed in my opinion because it forces responder to make an artificial bid that may get your side too high when, in fact, you want to stay low. I play what I feel is a much sounder, more natural, and easier to remember system. It is described fully in my movie on reverses
|CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.bridgesights.com/hondobridge/hondoviewer/hondoviewer.php?sf=reverses^*N|CP||AT|.|
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


AT| 

In summary, it works like this:

1. The only way for responder to force to game is to bid the 4th suit (analogous to 4th suit forcing). Any other bid by responder is not game forcing. If responder does not bid the 4th suit, and opener has a hand strong enough to force to game (18+), then it is up to opener to take charge and force to game.

2. The partnership cannot stop below 2NT. 
|
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


NT||

%%% 3
qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      3. Fourth-Suit Forcing      }
^-|cs||fp||va|4|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N^*N|cp||at|When the responder bids the fourth suit (the only suit not bid yet) on his second turn, it means he has a good hand. He does not promise any length or strength in the (fourth) suit he has bid.|
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


AT|

How strong a hand? I recommend playing it as a game force. This means the responder has at least opening-bid values (he knows that opposite his partner's opening bid there is enough combined strength for game). Examples are next.|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||
%%example
st||pn|,,,|md|3,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|Fourth-Suit Forcing - A|NT|^B@2
In this auction, responder's 2D says:|mb|1cp1hp1sp2d|an|Partner, I have enough for game (I might not have anything in diamonds).|
pg| ***** 56 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Why make such a bid? |
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


AT|In modern bridge, if responder had jumped at his second turn, for example:|
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


ub||
pg| ***** 59 ***** |


mb|3h|at| bid 3@H|
pg| ***** 60 ***** |


ub||
pg| ***** 61 ***** |


mb|3S|at| or bid 3@S,|
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


UB||
PG| ***** 63 ***** |


MB|3C|at| or bid 3@C,|
PG| ***** 64 ***** |


NT|^B@2
it would be invitational. In general, a second-round jump by responder is invitational. Accordingly, if he has more than an invitational hand he needs to make some other bid. Ergo, fourth-suit forcing. |
PG| ***** 65 ***** |


NT|^B@2
In each of the three auctions above, what if responder had a game-forcing hand with either hearts, spades, or clubs? In all cases he'd start with 2@D to set up the game force. On his next turn (he had better get one!) he clarifies his intentions with a natural (forcing) bid.|
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


NT||bt||
%%%%
cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|I highly recommend playing the 4th suit by responder (as an UPH) as 100% game forcing. Look out for the special auction of|
ht|e|cs|6|at|^B{|ia|,1cp1dp1hp1s|at|}|HT|E|AT|^M@2Some players choose to use this as the only exception. The 1@S bid is treated as a natural call (to try to locate a possible 4-4 spade fit), and the "fourth-suit forcing bid" becomes a jump to 2@S. It is not crucial that you make this exception'but just be aware that many partnerships do so.|
PG| ***** 67 ***** |


ht|j|at|^B@2
By a passed hand, the fourth suit should be natural and not forcing at all (a passed hand can't force to game).|
PG| ***** 68 ***** |


ht|m|at|^B{|ia|,1dp1sp2cp3h|at|}|HT|m|AT|^M@2I recommend that jumps in the fourth suit be played as natural and invitational. So, the auction on the left is made with a hand like:|ht|r|at|^B@2@SA Q J x x @HK J T x x @Dx x @Cx.|
PG| ***** 69 ***** |


AT|

In a 2/1 GF auction, the 4th suit is not needed to artificially force to game (you are already forced there) -- so it should be natural!|
PG| ***** 70 ***** |


